  "title": "Semiregular Polyhedra",
  "body": " Semiregular Polyhedra   Defining Semiregular Polyhedra  We now extend our collection of polyhedra by exploring what it means for a polyhedron to be semiregular and to construct some examples.   semiregular polyhedron  polyhedron semiregular  vertex arrangement polyhedron   A polyhedron is semiregular if it satisfies the following conditions:  Every face is a regular polygon.  At least two polygonal faces have a different number of sides.  The arrangement of polygons at every vertex of the polyhedron are the same.    The notation for a vertex arrangement of a polyhedron is the same as what we used for tilings. A cube would be denoted 4.4.4 because there are three squares meeting at any vertex of the cube.    Check your Understanding  Which regular polyhedron corresponds to the notation 3.3.3.3.3?   Does the number 3 correspond to the shape of the face or the number of faces that meet?    The icosahedron because five triangles meet at each vertex.     Some Examples of Semiregular Polyhedra     One example of a semi-regular polyhedron is the Great Rhombicosidodecahedron pictured in . Check that each vertex has the arrangement 4.6.10. What is the sum of the angles meeting at each vertex of the great rhombicosi dodecahedron?   Great Rhombicosidodecahedron   The front side of a great rhombicosidodecahedron. Five decagonal faces, eight hexagonal faces, and eight square faces are clearly visible, but there is a hint of a square and hexagon alonge the bottom edge.       Illustration produced by Robert Webb's Stella software as the creator of this image along with a link to the website: http:\/\/www.software3d.com\/Stella.php . Attribution, Link       Another Archimedean solid is the icosidodecahedron .   What is the vertex arrangement of the icosidodecahedron?    How many decagons are needed to create an icosidodecahedron? Be sure to count the ones you cannot see as well.    How many triangles are needed to create an icosidodecahedron?      The Icosidodecahedron   A picture of an icosidodecahedron     Illustration produced by Robert Webb's Stella software as the creator of this image along with a link to the website: http:\/\/www.software3d.com\/Stella.php . Attribution, Link      Choose one (or more) of the following vertex arrangements, , , , , , or and construct the semisregular polyhedron that has that vertex arrangement. If you are up for a challenge, you may choose , , or .   How many faces of each type does your semiregular polyhedron have?    What is the total number of vertices?    What is the total number of edges?        Families of Semiregular Polyhedra   Semiregular Polyhedra with Vertex Arrangement      Build the following semiregular polyhedron which has the following vertex arrangements. You will need these solids to answer the remainder of the questions in this task.                     Without building describe clearly what it would look like.    The polyhedra you just are called prisms . Use your constructions to complete .      Attributes of Prisms        Shape of base  Number of faces  Number of vertices  Number of edges    Triangle       Quadrilateral       Pentagon       Hexagon       Heptagon (7)  9  14  21    Octagon       -gon         Semiregular Polyhedra with Vertex Arrangement      Build the following semiregular polyhedron which has the following vertex arrangements. You will need these solids to answer the remainder of the questions in this task.    (a regular polyhedron)                      Without building describe clearly what it would look like.    The polyhedra you just are called antiprisms . Use your constructions to complete .      Attributes of Antiprisms    Shape of base  Number of faces  Number of vertices  Number of edges    Triangle  ?  ?  ?    Quadrilateral  ?  ?  ?    Pentagon  ?  ?  ?    Hexagon  ?  ?  ?    Heptagon (7)  16  14  28    Octagon  ?  ?  ?    -gon  ?  ?  ?       Compute for each row in and each row of . What do you notice?      Definitions  In this section we discovered two families of semiregular polygons, prisms and antiprisms. We can also create prisms and antiprisms which have faces are not regular. In particular, the sides of a prism need not be squares, they could be rectangles or other parallelograms. The sides of an antiprism do not need to be equilateral. Moreover, the bases of a prism or antiprism may be any polygon whatsoever.   prism   A prism is a polyhedron consisting of two congruent parallel polygonal faces joined by sides that are parallelograms (often rectangles).     antiprism   An antiprism is a polyhedron consisting of a pair of parallel congruent polygonal faces joined by sides that are triangles.    The two parallel congruent polygonal faces are called the bases of the prism or antiprism. The top base may be called the summit in which case the bottom would be called the base . Of course, we can sit a polyhedron on any of its faces. Sometimes the bases will be at the ends rather than at the top and bottom. base prism  summit prism  base antiprism  summit antiprism     "
