  "title": "Pyramids and Cones",
  "body": " Pyramids and Cones   Defining Pyramids and Cones  In this section, we will learn about pyramids and cones and how they are related to prisms and cylinders.   Pyramid  pyramid  apex pyramid  height pyramid   A pyramid is a polyhedron which may have any polygon as its base but the all remaining faces are triangles that share a common vertex called the apex . The height of the pyramid is measured from the apex to the plane containing the base along a line perpendicular to this plane.  We name each pyramid according to its base. Thus, a triangular pyramid has a triangular base, a square pyramid has a square base, and so forth. Also, the apex of the pyramid need not be directly above the center of the base; in fact, the apex may not be directly above any part of the pyramid.      Patterns with Pyramids    Use models and reasoning to complete .   Counting Parts of a Pyramid        Type of Pyramid  Number of faces  Number of vertices  Number of edges    Triangular pyramid  4  4  6    Quadrilateral pyramid       Pentagonal pyramid       Hexagonal pyramid       -gonal pyramid          What appears to be true about for each pyramid?      Measuring Pyramids  We shall compute measurements a specific example, the pyramid with height 4 and 3 by 4 rectangular base. Then we can attempt to generalize some of our observations to other pyramids and cylinders.   Exploring a Rectangular Pyramid   Throughout this activity, we will explore the rectangular pyramid that is created by folding the net in .   Rectangular Pyramid for    A net that can be folded to create a rectangular pyramid.     Constructing a pyramid from a net  Print a copy of this net, cut it out, and fold along the dashed lines to see that this forms a rectangular pyramid. Stiffer paper such as cardstock is recommended. What do you notice about the corner at ?   You will use this construction again near the end of this exploration. Keep it in good condition!   Finding Edge Lengths and Surface Area  Here is a rectangle with and . Angles , , , and are right angles and . Determine the following:  Determine   Determine .  Explain why and .  Determine   Use your knowledge of rectangles and triangles and the definition of surface area to determine the surface area of this rectangular pyramid.      With both prisms and pyramids, formulas exist to compute the surface area of some of the common types, but these formulas are not necessary. If we can compute the areas of each face, then the surface area is simply the sum of the areas of the faces.  How can we find the volume of a pyramid? It is a fact that the volume of a pyramid is exactly one-third of the volume of the prism with the same stretch distance. Since we know that the volume of a prism is , the volume of a pyramid must be where is the area of the base and is the stretch distance or height. In fact, this works for cones as well. The volume of a cone is since the area of the circular base is .    Exercises   Skills and Recall   Determine the volumes of the following solids:     Determine the surface area of the following solids:      Extending the Concepts  Visualizing the Volume Formula for a Rectangular Pyramid  Print the three nets in on stiff paper. The scale factor of any enlargements should be consistent. Cut out the nets and fold each to create a rectangular pyramid, taping the edges as needed.   Nets for   Nets for three rectangular pyramids; two have a 3 by 4-rectangular base and height 4. The other has a 4 by 4-square base and height 3.      Use the formula to determine the volume of each pyramid. Note that two pyramids should be identical.   Put the three pyramids together so that they form a -rectangular prism. How does this demonstrate that the formula holds for this particular pyramid?        "
